\begin_layout Definition
A 
\emph on
probability space
\emph default
 is a measure space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA,\Pr\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\Om\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default
, and denote the set of all probability measures on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\P\left(\Om\right)$
\end_inset

 if there is no ambiguity.
 An 
\emph on
event
\emph default
 is a measurable set 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\in\cA$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our purposes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om$
\end_inset

 will often be countable, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\cA$
\end_inset

 as the power set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Om$
\end_inset

.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 is uniquely defined by the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\om\right):=\Pr\left(\left\{ \om\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\om\in\Om$
\end_inset

.
 We will discuss specific probability spaces on combinatorial objects in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:random-structures"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\A\right)$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 occurs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Events will usually be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\A=\left\{ \om\in\Om:\, P\left(\om\right)\mbox{ holds}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\om\right)$
\end_inset

 is some property of an object 
\begin_inset Formula $\om$
\end_inset

.
 For clarity, we often abuse notation slightly and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(P\mbox{ holds}\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(\left\{ \om\in\Om:\, P\left(\om\right)\mbox{ holds}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

.
