 This motivates the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 is a random element which takes values in the measurable space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Om,\cA\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
distribution
\emph default
 (or 
\emph on
law
\emph default
) 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 with respect to an underlying probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr$
\end_inset

 is the pushforward measure with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

.
 That is, it is a probability measure defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}\left(\A\right)=\Pr\left(\X^{-1}\left(\A\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\subseteq\cA$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we occasionally use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lb{\X}:=\L{\X}$
\end_inset

 for ease of reading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth noting that in fact any probability measure is the distribution
 of some random element, so we can define a probability distribution in
 the abstract and then assert the existence of a random variable with that
 distribution.
 To see this, note that given a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{}\in\P\left(\Om\right)$
\end_inset

, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\X=\id_{\Om}$
\end_inset

 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}=\L{}$
